# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: centroid-tree-divide
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] In mathematics and physics, the **centroid**, also known as **geometric center** or **center of figure**, of a plane figure or solid figure is the mean position of all the points in the figure.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The same definition extends to any object in n -dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] In geometry, one often assumes uniform mass density, in which case the *barycenter* or *center of mass* coincides with the centroid.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] Informally, it can be understood as the point at which a cutout of the shape (with uniformly distributed mass) could be perfectly balanced on the tip of a pin.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] In physics, if variations in gravity are considered, then a *center of gravity* can be defined as the weighted mean of all points weighted by their specific weight.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] In geography, the centroid of a radial projection of a region of the Earth's surface to sea level is the region's geographical center.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] It is used as a substitute for the older terms "center of gravity" and "center of mass" when the purely geometrical aspects of that point are to be emphasized.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The term is particular to the English language; French, for instance, uses "*centre de gravité*" on most occasions, and other languages use terms of similar meaning.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The center of gravity, as the name indicates, is a notion that arose in mechanics, most likely in connection with building activities.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] It is uncertain when the idea first appeared, as the concept likely occurred to many people individually with minor differences.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] Nonetheless, the center of gravity of figures was studied extensively in Antiquity; Bossut credits Archimedes (287–212 BCE) with being the first to find the centroid of plane figures, although he never defines it.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] A treatment of centroids of solids by Archimedes has been lost.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] It is unlikely that Archimedes learned the theorem that the medians of a triangle meet in a point—the center of gravity of the triangle—directly from Euclid, as this proposition is not in the *Elements*.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The first explicit statement of this proposition is due to Heron of Alexandria (perhaps the first century CE) and occurs in his *Mechanics*.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] It may be added, in passing, that the proposition did not become common in the textbooks on plane geometry until the nineteenth century.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The geometric centroid of a convex object always lies in the object.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] A non-convex object might have a centroid that is outside the figure itself.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The centroid of a ring or a bowl, for example, lies in the object's central void.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] If the centroid is defined, it is a fixed point of all isometries in its symmetry group.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] In particular, the geometric centroid of an object lies in the intersection of all its hyperplanes of symmetry.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The centroid of many figures (regular polygon, regular polyhedron, cylinder, rectangle, rhombus, circle, sphere, ellipse, ellipsoid, superellipse, superellipsoid, etc.) can be determined by this principle alone.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] In particular, the centroid of a parallelogram is the meeting point of its two diagonals.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] This is not true of other quadrilaterals.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] For the same reason, the centroid of an object with translational symmetry is undefined (or lies outside the enclosing space), because a translation has no fixed point.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The centroid of a triangle is the intersection of the three medians of the triangle (each median connecting a vertex with the midpoint of the opposite side).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] For other properties of a triangle's centroid, see below.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The centroid of a uniformly dense planar lamina, such as in figure (a) below, may be determined experimentally by using a plumbline and a pin to find the collocated center of mass of a thin body of uniform density having the same shape.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The body is held by the pin, inserted at a point, off the presumed centroid in such a way that it can freely rotate around the pin; the plumb line is then dropped from the pin (figure b).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The position of the plumbline is traced on the surface, and the procedure is repeated with the pin inserted at any different point (or a number of points) off the centroid of the object.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The unique intersection point of these lines will be the centroid (figure c).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] Provided that the body is of uniform density, all lines made this way will include the centroid, and all lines will cross at exactly the same place.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] This method can be extended (in theory) to concave shapes where the centroid may lie outside the shape, and virtually to solids (again, of uniform density), where the centroid may lie within the body.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The (virtual) positions of the plumb lines need to be recorded by means other than by drawing them along the shape.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] For convex two-dimensional shapes, the centroid can be found by balancing the shape on a smaller shape, such as the top of a narrow cylinder.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The centroid occurs somewhere within the range of contact between the two shapes (and exactly at the point where the shape would balance on a pin).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] In principle, progressively narrower cylinders can be used to find the centroid to arbitrary precision.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] In practice air currents make this infeasible.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] However, by marking the overlap range from multiple balances, one can achieve a considerable level of accuracy.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] For example, the figure below (a) is easily divided into a square and a triangle, both with positive area; and a circular hole, with negative area (b).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The centroid of each part can be found in any list of centroids of simple shapes (c).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] Then the centroid of the figure is the weighted average of the three points.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The same formula holds for any three-dimensional objects, except that each $A_{i}$ should be the volume of $X_{i},$ rather than its area.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] It also holds for any subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{d},$ for any dimension $d,$ with the areas replaced by the d -dimensional measures of the parts.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] where the integrals are taken over the whole space $\mathbb {R} ^{n},$ and g is the characteristic function of the subset X of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}\!:\ g(x)=1$ if $x\in X$ and $g(x)=0$ otherwise.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] Note that the denominator is simply the measure of the set $X.$ This formula cannot be applied if the set X has zero measure, or if either integral diverges.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] where A is the area of the region (given by ${\textstyle \int _{a}^{b}{\bigl (}f(x)-g(x){\bigr )}dx}$ ).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] An integraph (a relative of the planimeter) can be used to find the centroid of an object of irregular shape with smooth (or piecewise smooth) boundary.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The mathematical principle involved is a special case of Green's theorem.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] This is a method of determining the centroid of an L-shaped object.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] Divide the shape into two other rectangles, as shown in fig 3.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] Find the centroids of these two rectangles by drawing the diagonals.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] As the centroid of the shape must lie along $AB$ and also along $CD,$ it must be at the intersection of these two lines, at $O.$ The point O might lie inside or outside the L-shaped object.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The centroid of a triangle is the point of intersection of its medians (the lines joining each vertex with the midpoint of the opposite side).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The centroid divides each of the medians in the ratio $2:1,$ which is to say it is located ${\tfrac {1}{3}}$ of the distance from each side to the opposite vertex (see figures at right).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] Its Cartesian coordinates are the means of the coordinates of the three vertices.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The centroid is also the physical center of mass if the triangle is made from a uniform sheet of material; or if all the mass is concentrated at the three vertices, and evenly divided among them.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] On the other hand, if the mass is distributed along the triangle's perimeter, with uniform linear density, then the center of mass lies at the Spieker center (the incenter of the medial triangle), which does not (in general) coincide with the geometric centroid of the full triangle.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The area of the triangle is ${\tfrac {3}{2}}$ times the length of any side times the perpendicular distance from the side to the centroid.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The isogonal conjugate of a triangle's centroid is its symmedian point.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] Any of the three medians through the centroid divides the triangle's area in half.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] A triangle's centroid is the point that maximizes the product of the directed distances of a point from the triangle's sidelines.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] Let $ABC$ be a triangle, let G be its centroid, and let $D,E,F$ be the midpoints of segments $BC,CA,AB,$ respectively.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The centroid of a non-triangular polygon is not the same as its *vertex centroid*, considering only its vertex set (as the centroid of a finite set of points; ).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The centroid of a cone or pyramid is located on the line segment that connects the apex to the centroid of the base.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] For a solid cone or pyramid, the centroid is ${\tfrac {1}{4}}$ the distance from the base to the apex.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] For a cone or pyramid that is just a shell (hollow) with no base, the centroid is ${\tfrac {1}{3}}$ the distance from the base plane to the apex.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] A tetrahedron is an object in three-dimensional space having four triangles as its faces.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] A line segment joining a vertex of a tetrahedron with the centroid of the opposite face is called a *median*, and a line segment joining the midpoints of two opposite edges is called a *bimedian*.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] Hence there are four medians and three bimedians.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] These seven line segments all meet at the *centroid* of the tetrahedron.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The medians are divided by the centroid in the ratio $3:1.$ The centroid of a tetrahedron is the midpoint between its Monge point and circumcenter (center of the circumscribed sphere).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] These three points define the *Euler line* of the tetrahedron that is analogous to the Euler line of a triangle.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] These results generalize to any n -dimensional simplex in the following way.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The geometric centroid coincides with the center of mass if the mass is uniformly distributed over the whole simplex, or concentrated at the vertices as $n+1$ equal masses.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The centroid of a solid hemisphere (i.e. half of a solid ball) divides the line segment connecting the sphere's center to the hemisphere's pole in the ratio $3:5$ (i.e. it lies ${\tfrac {3}{8}}$ of the way from the center to the pole).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/centroid] The centroid of a hollow hemisphere (i.e. half of a hollow sphere) divides the line segment connecting the sphere's center to the hemisphere's pole in half.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In computer science, **divide and conquer** is an algorithm design paradigm.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] A divide-and-conquer algorithm recursively breaks down a problem into two or more sub-problems of the same or related type, until these become simple enough to be solved directly.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The solutions to the sub-problems are then combined to give a solution to the original problem.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Designing efficient divide-and-conquer algorithms can be difficult.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] As in mathematical induction, it is often necessary to generalize the problem to make it amenable to a recursive solution.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The correctness of a divide-and-conquer algorithm is usually proved by mathematical induction, and its computational cost is often determined by solving recurrence relations.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The divide-and-conquer paradigm is often used to find an optimal solution of a problem.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Its basic idea is to decompose a given problem into two or more similar, but simpler, subproblems, to solve them in turn, and to compose their solutions to solve the given problem.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Problems of sufficient simplicity are solved directly.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, to sort a given list of *n* natural numbers, split it into two lists of about *n*/2 numbers each, sort each of them in turn, and interleave both results appropriately to obtain the sorted version of the given list (see the picture).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This approach is known as the merge sort algorithm.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The name "divide and conquer" is sometimes applied to algorithms that reduce each problem to only one sub-problem, such as the binary search algorithm for finding a record in a sorted list (or its analogue in numerical computing, the bisection algorithm for root finding).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] These algorithms can be implemented more efficiently than general divide-and-conquer algorithms; in particular, if they use tail recursion, they can be converted into simple loops.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Under this broad definition, however, every algorithm that uses recursion or loops could be regarded as a "divide-and-conquer algorithm".
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Therefore, some authors consider that the name "divide and conquer" should be used only when each problem may generate two or more subproblems.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The name **decrease and conquer** has been proposed instead for the single-subproblem class.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Early examples of these algorithms are primarily decrease and conquer – the original problem is successively broken down into *single* subproblems, and indeed can be solved iteratively.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Binary search, a decrease-and-conquer algorithm where the subproblems are of roughly half the original size, has a long history.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] While a clear description of the algorithm on computers appeared in 1946 in an article by John Mauchly, the idea of using a sorted list of items to facilitate searching dates back at least as far as Babylonia in 200 BC.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Another ancient decrease-and-conquer algorithm is the Euclidean algorithm to compute the greatest common divisor of two numbers by reducing the numbers to smaller and smaller equivalent subproblems, which dates to several centuries BC.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] An early two-subproblem D&C algorithm that was specifically developed for computers and properly analyzed is the merge sort algorithm, invented by John von Neumann in 1945.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Another notable example is the algorithm invented by Anatolii A.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Karatsuba in 1960 that could multiply two *n*-digit numbers in $O(n^{\log _{2}3})$ operations (in Big O notation).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This algorithm disproved Andrey Kolmogorov's 1956 conjecture that $\Omega (n^{2})$ operations would be required for that task.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This is related to a radix sort, described for punch-card sorting machines as early as 1929.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide and conquer is a powerful tool for solving conceptually difficult problems: all it requires is a way of breaking the problem into sub-problems, of solving the trivial cases, and of combining sub-problems to the original problem.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Similarly, decrease and conquer only requires reducing the problem to a single smaller problem, such as the classic Tower of Hanoi puzzle, which reduces moving a tower of height n to move a tower of height $n-1$ .
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The divide-and-conquer paradigm often helps in the discovery of efficient algorithms.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] It was the key, for example, to Karatsuba's fast multiplication method, the quicksort and mergesort algorithms, the Strassen algorithm for matrix multiplication, and fast Fourier transforms.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In all these examples, the D&C approach led to an improvement in the asymptotic cost of the solution.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For other types of divide-and-conquer approaches, running times can also be generalized.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] If, instead, the work of splitting the problem and combining the partial solutions take $cn^{2}$ time, and there are 2 subproblems where each has size ${\frac {n}{2}}$ , then the running time of the divide-and-conquer algorithm is bounded by $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms are naturally adapted for execution in multi-processor machines, especially shared-memory systems where the communication of data between processors does not need to be planned in advance because distinct sub-problems can be executed on different processors.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms naturally tend to make efficient use of memory caches.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The reason is that once a sub-problem is small enough, it and all its sub-problems can, in principle, be solved within the cache, without accessing the slower main memory.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] An algorithm designed to exploit the cache in this way is called *cache-oblivious*, because it does not contain the cache size as an explicit parameter.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Moreover, D&C algorithms can be designed for important algorithms (e.g., sorting, FFTs, and matrix multiplication) to be *optimal* cache-oblivious algorithms–they use the cache in a probably optimal way, in an asymptotic sense, regardless of the cache size.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The same advantage exists with regards to other hierarchical storage systems, such as NUMA or virtual memory, as well as for multiple levels of cache: once a sub-problem is small enough, it can be solved within a given level of the hierarchy, without accessing the higher (slower) levels.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In computations with rounded arithmetic, e.g. with floating-point numbers, a divide-and-conquer algorithm may yield more accurate results than a superficially equivalent iterative method.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, one can add *N* numbers either by a simple loop that adds each datum to a single variable, or by a D&C algorithm called pairwise summation that breaks the data set into two halves, recursively computes the sum of each half, and then adds the two sums.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] While the second method performs the same number of additions as the first and pays the overhead of the recursive calls, it is usually more accurate.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms are naturally implemented as recursive procedures.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In that case, the partial sub-problems leading to the one currently being solved are automatically stored in the procedure call stack.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] A recursive function is a function that calls itself within its definition.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Divide-and-conquer algorithms can also be implemented by a non-recursive program that stores the partial sub-problems in some explicit data structure, such as a stack, queue, or priority queue.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This approach allows more freedom in the choice of the sub-problem that is to be solved next, a feature that is important in some applications — e.g. in breadth-first recursion and the branch-and-bound method for function optimization.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This approach is also the standard solution in programming languages that do not provide support for recursive procedures.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In recursive implementations of D&C algorithms, one must make sure that there is sufficient memory allocated for the recursion stack, otherwise, the execution may fail because of stack overflow.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] D&C algorithms that are time-efficient often have relatively small recursion depth.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, the quicksort algorithm can be implemented so that it never requires more than $\log _{2}n$ nested recursive calls to sort n items.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Stack overflow can be difficult to prevent when using recursive procedures, since many compilers treat the recursion stack as a contiguous block of memory, and some reserve a fixed amount of space for it.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In addition, compilers may store more information on the recursion stack than is strictly required, including the return address, unchanged parameters, and the procedure’s local variables.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] As a result, the likelihood of stack overflow may be reduced by limiting the number of parameters and local variables in the recursive procedure, or by replacing recursion with an explicit stack data structure.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In any recursive algorithm, there is considerable freedom in the choice of the *base cases*, the small subproblems that are solved directly in order to terminate the recursion.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Choosing the smallest or simplest possible base cases is more elegant and usually leads to simpler programs, because there are fewer cases to consider and they are easier to solve.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, a Fast Fourier Transform algorithm could stop the recursion when the input is a single sample, and the quicksort list-sorting algorithm could stop when the input is the empty list; in both examples, there is only one base case to consider, and it requires no processing.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] On the other hand, efficiency often improves if the recursion is stopped at relatively large base cases, and these are solved non-recursively, resulting in a hybrid algorithm.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] This strategy avoids the overhead of recursive calls that do little or no work and may also allow the use of specialized non-recursive algorithms that, for those base cases, are more efficient than explicit recursion.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] A general procedure for a simple hybrid recursive algorithm is *short-circuiting the base case*, also known as *arm's-length recursion*.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In this case, whether the next step will result in the base case is checked before the function call, avoiding an unnecessary function call.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, in a tree, rather than recursing to a child node and then checking whether it is null, checking null before recursing avoids half the function calls in some algorithms on binary trees.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Since a D&C algorithm eventually reduces each problem or sub-problem instance to a large number of base instances, these often dominate the overall cost of the algorithm, especially when the splitting/joining overhead is low.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Note that these considerations do not depend on whether recursion is implemented by the compiler or by an explicit stack.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Thus, for example, many library implementations of quicksort will switch to a simple loop-based insertion sort (or similar) algorithm once the number of items to be sorted is sufficiently small.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Note that, if the empty list were the only base case, sorting a list with n entries would entail maximally n quicksort calls that would do nothing but return immediately.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Increasing the base cases to lists of size 2 or less will eliminate most of those do-nothing calls, and more generally a base case larger than 2 is typically used to reduce the fraction of time spent in function-call overhead or stack manipulation.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For example, this approach is used in some efficient FFT implementations, where the base cases are unrolled implementations of divide-and-conquer FFT algorithms for a set of fixed sizes.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Source-code generation methods may be used to produce the large number of separate base cases desirable to implement this strategy efficiently.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] The generalized version of this idea is known as recursion "unrolling" or "coarsening", and various techniques have been proposed for automating the procedure of enlarging the base case.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] For some problems, the branched recursion may end up evaluating the same sub-problem many times over.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] In such cases it may be worth identifying and saving the solutions to these overlapping subproblems, a technique which is commonly known as memoization.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/divide-and-conquer-algorithm] Followed to the limit, it leads to bottom-up divide-and-conquer algorithms such as dynamic programming.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] In mathematics, a **graph partition** is the reduction of a graph to a smaller graph by partitioning its set of nodes into mutually exclusive groups.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Edges of the original graph that cross between the groups will produce edges in the partitioned graph.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] If the number of resulting edges is small compared to the original graph, then the partitioned graph may be better suited for analysis and problem-solving than the original.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Finding a partition that simplifies graph analysis is a hard problem, but one that has applications to scientific computing, VLSI circuit design, and task scheduling in multiprocessor computers, among others.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Recently, the graph partition problem has gained importance due to its application for clustering and detection of cliques in social, pathological and biological networks.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] For a survey on recent trends in computational methods and applications see Buluc et al.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Two common examples of graph partitioning are minimum cut and maximum cut problems.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Typically, graph partition problems fall under the category of NP-hard problems.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Solutions to these problems are generally derived using heuristics and approximation algorithms.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] However, uniform graph partitioning or a balanced graph partition problem can be shown to be NP-complete to approximate within any finite factor.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Even for special graph classes such as trees and grids, no reasonable approximation algorithms exist, unless P=NP.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Grids are a particularly interesting case since they model the graphs resulting from Finite Element Model (FEM) simulations.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] When not only the number of edges between the components is approximated, but also the sizes of the components, it can be shown that no reasonable fully polynomial algorithms exist for these graphs.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Consider a graph *G* = (*V*, *E*), where *V* denotes the set of *n* vertices and *E* the set of edges.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] For a (*k*,*v*) balanced partition problem, the objective is to partition *G* into *k* components of at most size *v* · (*n*/*k*), while minimizing the capacity of the edges between separate components.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Also, given *G* and an integer *k* > 1, partition *V* into *k* parts (subsets) *V*1, *V*2, ..., *Vk* such that the parts are disjoint and have equal size, and the number of edges with endpoints in different parts is minimized.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Such partition problems have been discussed in literature as bicriteria-approximation or resource augmentation approaches.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] A common extension is to hypergraphs, where an edge can connect more than two vertices.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] A hyperedge is not cut if all vertices are in one partition, and cut exactly once otherwise, no matter how many vertices are on each side.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] This usage is common in electronic design automation.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] For a specific (*k*, 1 + *ε*) balanced partition problem, we seek to find a minimum cost partition of *G* into *k* components with each component containing a maximum of (1 + *ε*)·(*n*/*k*) nodes.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] We compare the cost of this approximation algorithm to the cost of a (*k*,1) cut, wherein each of the *k* components must have the same size of (*n*/*k*) nodes each, thus being a more restricted problem.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] We already know that (2,1) cut is the minimum bisection problem and it is NP-complete.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Next, we assess a 3-partition problem wherein *n* = 3*k*, which is also bounded in polynomial time.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Now, if we assume that we have a finite approximation algorithm for (*k*, 1)-balanced partition, then, either the 3-partition instance can be solved using the balanced (*k*,1) partition in *G* or it cannot be solved.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] If the 3-partition instance can be solved, then (*k*, 1)-balanced partitioning problem in *G* can be solved without cutting any edge.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Otherwise, if the 3-partition instance cannot be solved, the optimum (*k*, 1)-balanced partitioning in *G* will cut at least one edge.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] An approximation algorithm with a finite approximation factor has to differentiate between these two cases.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Hence, it can solve the 3-partition problem which is a contradiction under the assumption that *P* = *NP*.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Thus, it is evident that (*k*,1)-balanced partitioning problem has no polynomial-time approximation algorithm with a finite approximation factor unless *P* = *NP*.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] The planar separator theorem states that any *n*-vertex planar graph can be partitioned into roughly equal parts by the removal of O(√*n*) vertices.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] This is not a partition in the sense described above, because the partition set consists of vertices rather than edges.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] However, the same result also implies that every planar graph of bounded degree has a balanced cut with O(√*n*) edges.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Since graph partitioning is a hard problem, practical solutions are based on heuristics.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] There are two broad categories of methods, local and global.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Well-known local methods are the Kernighan–Lin algorithm, and Fiduccia-Mattheyses algorithms, which were the first effective 2-way cuts by local search strategies.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Their major drawback is the arbitrary initial partitioning of the vertex set, which can affect the final solution quality.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Global approaches rely on properties of the entire graph and do not rely on an arbitrary initial partition.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] The most common example is spectral partitioning, where a partition is derived from approximate eigenvectors of the adjacency matrix, or spectral clustering that groups graph vertices using the eigendecomposition of the graph Laplacian matrix.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] A multi-level graph partitioning algorithm works by applying one or more stages.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Each stage reduces the size of the graph by collapsing vertices and edges, partitions the smaller graph, then maps back and refines this partition of the original graph.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] A wide variety of partitioning and refinement methods can be applied within the overall multi-level scheme.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] In many cases, this approach can give both fast execution times and very high quality results.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] One widely used example of such an approach is METIS, a graph partitioner, and hMETIS, the corresponding partitioner for hypergraphs.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] An alternative approach originated from and implemented, e.g., in scikit-learn is spectral clustering with the partitioning determined from eigenvectors of the graph Laplacian matrix for the original graph computed by LOBPCG solver with multigrid preconditioning.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Given a graph $G=(V,E)$ with adjacency matrix A , where an entry $A_{ij}$ implies an edge between node i and j , and degree matrix D , which is a diagonal matrix, where each diagonal entry of a row i , $d_{ii}$ , represents the node degree of node i .
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] The Laplacian matrix L is defined as $L=D-A$ .
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] of the number of edges that actually cross this cut to the number of pairs of vertices that could support such edges.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Spectral graph partitioning can be motivated by analogy with partitioning of a vibrating string or a mass-spring system and similarly extended to the case of negative weights of the graph.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] In such a scenario, the second smallest eigenvalue ( $\lambda _{2}$ ) of L , yields a *lower bound* on the optimal cost ( c ) of ratio-cut partition with $c\geq {\frac {\lambda _{2}}{n}}$ .
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] The eigenvector ( $V_{2}$ ) corresponding to $\lambda _{2}$ , called the *Fiedler vector*, bisects the graph into only two communities based on the ***sign** of the corresponding vector entry*.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Division into a larger number of communities can be achieved by repeated *bisection* or by using *multiple eigenvectors* corresponding to the smallest eigenvalues.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] The examples in Figures 1,2 illustrate the spectral bisection approach.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Minimum cut partitioning however fails when the number of communities to be partitioned, or the partition sizes are unknown.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] For instance, optimizing the cut size for free group sizes puts all vertices in the same community.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Additionally, cut size may be the wrong thing to minimize since a good division is not just one with small number of edges between communities.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] This motivated the use of Modularity (Q) as a metric to optimize a balanced graph partition.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] The example in Figure 3 illustrates 2 instances of the same graph such that in *(a)* modularity (Q) is the partitioning metric and in *(b)*, ratio-cut is the partitioning metric.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Another objective function used for graph partitioning is Conductance which is the ratio between the number of cut edges and the volume of the smallest part.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Conductance is related to electrical flows and random walks.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] The Cheeger bound guarantees that spectral bisection provides partitions with nearly optimal conductance.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] The quality of this approximation depends on the second smallest eigenvalue of the Laplacian λ2.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Graph partition can be useful for identifying the minimal set of nodes or links that should be immunized in order to stop epidemics.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Spin models have been used for clustering of multivariate data wherein similarities are translated into coupling strengths.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] The properties of ground state spin configuration can be directly interpreted as communities.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Thus, a graph is partitioned to minimize the Hamiltonian of the partitioned graph.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] The Hamiltonian (H) is derived by assigning the following partition rewards and penalties.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Additionally, Kernel-PCA-based Spectral clustering takes a form of least squares Support Vector Machine framework, and hence it becomes possible to project the data entries to a kernel induced feature space that has maximal variance, thus implying a high separation between the projected communities.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Some methods express graph partitioning as a multi-criteria optimization problem which can be solved using local methods expressed in a game theoretic framework where each node makes a decision on the partition it chooses.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] For very large-scale distributed graphs classical partition methods might not apply (e.g., spectral partitioning, Metis) since they require full access to graph data in order to perform global operations.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] For such large-scale scenarios distributed graph partitioning is used to perform partitioning through asynchronous local operations only.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] scikit-learn implements spectral clustering with the partitioning determined from eigenvectors of the graph Laplacian matrix for the original graph computed by ARPACK, or by LOBPCG solver with multigrid preconditioning.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] METIS is a graph partitioning family by Karypis and Kumar.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Among this family, kMetis aims at greater partitioning speed, hMetis, applies to hypergraphs and aims at partition quality, and ParMetis is a parallel implementation of the Metis graph partitioning algorithm.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] KaHyPar is a multilevel hypergraph partitioning framework providing direct k-way and recursive bisection based partitioning algorithms.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] It instantiates the multilevel approach in its most extreme version, removing only a single vertex in every level of the hierarchy.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] By using this very fine grained *n*-level approach combined with strong local search heuristics, it computes solutions of very high quality.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Scotch is graph partitioning framework by Pellegrini.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] It uses recursive multilevel bisection and includes sequential as well as parallel partitioning techniques.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Jostle is a sequential and parallel graph partitioning solver developed by Chris Walshaw.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] The commercialized version of this partitioner is known as NetWorks.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Party implements the Bubble/shape-optimized framework and the Helpful Sets algorithm.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] The software packages DibaP and its MPI-parallel variant PDibaP by Meyerhenke implement the Bubble framework using diffusion; DibaP also uses AMG-based techniques for coarsening and solving linear systems arising in the diffusive approach.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] Sanders and Schulz released a graph partitioning package KaHIP (Karlsruhe High Quality Partitioning) that implements for example flow-based methods, more-localized local searches and several parallel and sequential meta-heuristics.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/graph-partition] The tools Parkway by Trifunovic and Knottenbelt as well as Zoltan by Devine et al. focus on hypergraph partitioning.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] In graph theory, a **tree** is an undirected graph in which every pair of distinct vertices is connected by *exactly one* path, or equivalently, a connected acyclic undirected graph.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] A **forest** is an undirected graph in which any two vertices are connected by *at most one* path, or equivalently an acyclic undirected graph, or equivalently a disjoint union of trees.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] A directed tree, oriented tree, polytree, or singly connected network is a directed acyclic graph (DAG) whose underlying undirected graph is a tree.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] A polyforest (or directed forest or oriented forest) is a directed acyclic graph whose underlying undirected graph is a forest.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] The various kinds of data structures referred to as trees in computer science have underlying graphs that are trees in graph theory, although such data structures are generally rooted trees.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] A rooted tree may be directed, called a directed rooted tree, either making all its edges point away from the root—in which case it is called an arborescence or out-tree—or making all its edges point towards the root—in which case it is called an anti-arborescence or in-tree.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] A rooted tree itself has been defined by some authors as a directed graph.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] A rooted forest is a disjoint union of rooted trees.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] The term *tree* was coined in 1857 by the British mathematician Arthur Cayley.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] It may, however, be considered as a forest consisting of zero trees.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] An *internal vertex* (or inner vertex) is a vertex of degree at least 2.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] Similarly, an *external vertex* (or outer vertex, terminal vertex or leaf) is a vertex of degree 1.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] A branch vertex in a tree is a vertex of degree at least 3.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] An *irreducible tree* (or series-reduced tree) is a tree in which there is no vertex of degree 2 (enumerated at sequence A000014 in the OEIS).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] A *forest* is an undirected acyclic graph or equivalently a disjoint union of trees.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] Trivially so, each connected component of a forest is a tree.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] As special cases, the order-zero graph (a forest consisting of zero trees), a single tree, and an edgeless graph, are examples of forests.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] Since for every tree *V* − *E* = 1, we can easily count the number of trees that are within a forest by subtracting the difference between total vertices and total edges.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] *V* − *E* = number of trees in a forest.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] A *polytree* (or *directed tree* or *oriented tree* or *singly connected network*) is a directed acyclic graph (DAG) whose underlying undirected graph is a tree.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] In other words, if we replace its directed edges with undirected edges, we obtain an undirected graph that is both connected and acyclic.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] Some authors restrict the phrase "directed tree" to the case where the edges are all directed towards a particular vertex, or all directed away from a particular vertex (see arborescence).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] A *polyforest* (or directed forest or oriented forest) is a directed acyclic graph whose underlying undirected graph is a forest.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] In other words, if we replace its directed edges with undirected edges, we obtain an undirected graph that is acyclic.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] As with directed trees, some authors restrict the phrase "directed forest" to the case where the edges of each connected component are all directed towards a particular vertex, or all directed away from a particular vertex (see branching).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] A *rooted tree* is a tree in which one vertex has been designated the root.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] The edges of a rooted tree can be assigned a natural orientation, either away from or towards the root, in which case the structure becomes a directed rooted tree.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] When a directed rooted tree has an orientation away from the root, it is called an *arborescence* or *out-tree*; when it has an orientation towards the root, it is called an *anti-arborescence* or *in-tree*.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] The tree-order is the partial ordering on the vertices of a tree with *u* < *v* only if the unique path from the root to v passes through u.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] A rooted tree T that is a subgraph of some graph G is a normal tree if the ends of every T-path in G are comparable in this tree-order (Diestel 2005, p.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] Rooted trees, often with an additional structure such as an ordering of the neighbors at each vertex, are a key data structure in computer science; see tree data structure.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] In a context where trees typically have a root, a tree without any designated root is called a *free tree*.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] A *labeled tree* is a tree in which each vertex is given a unique label.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] The vertices of a labeled tree on n vertices (for nonnegative integers n) are typically given the labels 1, 2, …, *n*.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] A *recursive tree* is a labeled rooted tree where the vertex labels respect the tree order (i.e., if *u* < *v* for two vertices u and v, then the label of u is smaller than the label of v).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] In a rooted tree, the **parent** of a vertex v is the vertex connected to v on the path to the root; every vertex has a unique parent, except the root has no parent.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] A *child* of a vertex v is a vertex of which v is the parent.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] An *ascendant* of a vertex v is any vertex that is either the parent of v or is (recursively) an ascendant of a parent of v.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] A *descendant* of a vertex v is any vertex that is either a child of v or is (recursively) a descendant of a child of v.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] A *sibling* to a vertex v is any other vertex on the tree that shares a parent with v.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] An *internal vertex* is a vertex that is not a leaf.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] The *height* of a vertex in a rooted tree is the length of the longest downward path to a leaf from that vertex.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] The *height* of the tree is the height of the root.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] The *depth* of a vertex is the length of the path to its root (*root path*).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] The depth of a tree is the maximum depth of any vertex.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] Depth is commonly needed in the manipulation of the various self-balancing trees, AVL trees in particular.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] The root has depth zero, leaves have height zero, and a tree with only a single vertex (hence both a root and leaf) has depth and height zero.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] Conventionally, an empty tree (a tree with no vertices, if such are allowed) has depth and height −1.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] A *k-ary tree* (for nonnegative integers k) is a rooted tree in which each vertex has at most k children.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] 2-ary trees are often called *binary trees*, while 3-ary trees are sometimes called *ternary trees*.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] An *ordered tree* (alternatively, *plane tree* or *positional tree*) is a rooted tree in which an ordering is specified for the children of each vertex.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] This is called a "plane tree" because an ordering of the children is equivalent to an embedding of the tree in the plane, with the root at the top and the children of each vertex lower than that vertex.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] Given an embedding of a rooted tree in the plane, if one fixes a direction of children, say left to right, then an embedding gives an ordering of the children.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] Conversely, given an ordered tree, and conventionally drawing the root at the top, then the child vertices in an ordered tree can be drawn left-to-right, yielding an essentially unique planar embedding.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] Cayley's formula states that there are *n**n*−2 trees on n labeled vertices.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] A more general problem is to count spanning trees in an undirected graph, which is addressed by the matrix tree theorem.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] (Cayley's formula is the special case of spanning trees in a complete graph.) The similar problem of counting all the subtrees regardless of size is #P-complete in the general case (Jerrum (1994)).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] Counting the number of unlabeled free trees is a harder problem.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/tree-graph-theory] No closed formula for the number *t*(*n*) of trees with n vertices up to graph isomorphism is known.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/vertex-separator] In graph theory, a vertex subset ⁠ $S\subset V$ ⁠ is a **vertex separator** (or **vertex cut**, **separating set**) for nonadjacent vertices a and b if the removal of S from the graph separates a and b into distinct connected components.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/vertex-separator] Consider a grid graph with r rows and c columns; the total number n of vertices is *r* × *c*.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/vertex-separator] For instance, in the illustration, *r* = 5, *c* = 8, and *n* = 40.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/vertex-separator] If r is odd, there is a single central row, and otherwise there are two rows equally close to the center; similarly, if c is odd, there is a single central column, and otherwise there are two columns equally close to the center.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/vertex-separator] Choosing S to be any of these central rows or columns, and removing S from the graph, partitions the graph into two smaller connected subgraphs A and B, each of which has at most *n*⁄2 vertices.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/vertex-separator] If *r* ≤ *c* (as in the illustration), then choosing a central column will give a separator S with $r\leq {\sqrt {n}}$ vertices, and similarly if *c* ≤ *r* then choosing a central row will give a separator with at most ${\sqrt {n}}$ vertices.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/vertex-separator] Thus, every grid graph has a separator S of size at most ${\sqrt {n}},$ the removal of which partitions it into two connected components, each of size at most *n*⁄2.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/vertex-separator] To give another class of examples, every free tree T has a separator S consisting of a single vertex, the removal of which partitions T into two or more connected components, each of size at most *n*⁄2.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/vertex-separator] More precisely, there is always exactly one or exactly two vertices, which amount to such a separator, depending on whether the tree is centered or bicentered.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/vertex-separator] As opposed to these examples, not all vertex separators are *balanced*, but that property is most useful for applications in computer science, such as the planar separator theorem.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/vertex-separator] Let S be an (*a*,*b*)-separator, that is, a vertex subset that separates two nonadjacent vertices a and b.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/vertex-separator] Then S is a *minimal* (*a*,*b*)-*separator* if no proper subset of S separates a and b.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/vertex-separator] More generally, S is called a *minimal separator* if it is a minimal separator for some pair (*a*,*b*) of nonadjacent vertices.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/vertex-separator] Notice that this is different from *minimal separating set* which says that no proper subset of S is a minimal (*u*,*v*)-separator for any pair of vertices (*u*,*v*).
[src:centroid-tree-divide/vertex-separator] The minimal (*a*,*b*)-separators also form an algebraic structure: For two fixed vertices a and b of a given graph G, an (*a*,*b*)-separator S can be regarded as a *predecessor* of another (*a*,*b*)-separator T, if every path from a to b meets S before it meets T.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/vertex-separator] More rigorously, the predecessor relation is defined as follows: Let S and T be two (*a*,*b*)-separators in G.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/vertex-separator] Then S is a predecessor of T, in symbols $S\sqsubseteq _{a,b}^{G}T$ , if for each *x* ∈ *S* \ *T*, every path connecting x to b meets T.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/vertex-separator] It follows from the definition that the predecessor relation yields a preorder on the set of all (*a*,*b*)-separators.
[src:centroid-tree-divide/vertex-separator] Furthermore, Escalante (1972) proved that the predecessor relation gives rise to a complete lattice when restricted to the set of *minimal* (*a*,*b*)-separators in G.
